ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Netflix=E2=80=99s forays into the live event bu=
siness have been well
documented. Last month, it carried a night of boxing featuring a reality st=
ar fighting a 58-year-old former champ that was so popular it nearly broke =
the internet. On January 6, the company will start carrying <em>WWE Raw</em=
> weekly as part of a 10-year, $5 billion deal. And, of course, in two days=
 it will air two NFL games featuring four of the league=E2=80=99s most popu=
lar teams: the Chiefs, Steelers, Ravens, and Texans.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">Netflix executives ostensibly believe that live events,=
 including sports, will help the company build out its advertising tier. An=
d there=E2=80=99s no doubt that its deal for Women=E2=80=99s World Cup righ=
ts marks its biggest push into the sports arena. It=E2=80=99s not hard to e=
nvision a scenario where Netflix is aggressive in bidding for the Men=E2=80=
=99s World Cup rights in 2030 and 2034 when they become available.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">
But Netflix=E2=80=99s recent activity doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily mean that=
 the company is going all-in on sports rights. Netflix executives have alwa=
ys said that they are interested in one-off events, perhaps as a way to def=
ray production costs and other CapEx. The Women=E2=80=99s World Cup deal is=
 an extension of this strategy, though this =E2=80=9Cone-off event=E2=80=9D=
 comprises multiple games over several weeks.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">If you ta=
lk to a Netflix
exec long enough, they=E2=80=99ll almost certainly use the hackneyed phrase=
 =E2=80=9Ccrawl, walk, run=E2=80=9D to define their manifest destiny in the=
 industry. Netflix traditionally approaches new initiatives slowly while ho=
ning its investment thesis. It=E2=80=99s been operating this way at least s=
ince it started dabbling in original series, as investments in shows like <=
em>Lilyhammer </em>paved the way for <em>House of Cards </em>and <em>Orange=
 Is the New Black</em>. Netflix crawled when it carried made-for-TV tennis,=
 golf,
and boxing matches. Its move into the NFL, WWE, and FIFA marks more of a wa=
lking phase. After all, as <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpb=
F9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUOWtrT3BmdHBDNEZhSWgtLXBpOD0iLCJocmVmIjoi=
aHR0cHM6Ly92YXJpZXR5LmNvbS8yMDI0L3R2L25ld3MvYmV5b25jZS1uZmwtaGFsZnRpbWUtc2h=
vdy1jaHJpc3RtYXMtbmV0ZmxpeC1yZXdhdGNoLTEyMzYyNTgwMTEvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaG=
UrVmFyc2l0eSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODEyJTJGMjMlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250Z=
W50PVRoZStWYXJzaXR5Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkYyMyUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRt=
X21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXR=
tX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMm=
EiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoyMDI1NjgyfQ/2f4235441a84cec5a0af0bce8ced2d809bed577258fa1b=
a532b467a94ed0e206" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;"><em>=
Variety</em></a> reported, the two NFL games (and <strong>Beyonc=C3=A9</str=
ong>=E2=80=99s halftime show) will disappear from Netflix three hours after=
 the livestream ends. That=E2=80=99s definitely not =E2=80=9Crunning=E2=80=
=9D mode yet=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin:
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">The hope among all l=
eagues and conferences is that Netflix soon segues to the next phase of its=
 development. After all, the NFL is expected to exercise an out in its broa=
dcast deals by 2030. The MLB and NHL national media rights deals are up, to=
o, in 2028. Some wonder aloud if Netflix is already poised to take over the=
 sports media business as surreptitiously as it did Hollywood.</p></div>
